<!-- PHYSICS TAB -->
<div id="tab-physics" style="display:none">
    <div class="section-title" style="margin-bottom:12px">Forward-Model Physics — Triple-Combo Reference</div>
    <div class="physics-grid">
        <div class="phys-card">
            <div class="phys-title">ρb — Bulk Density (Gardner Mixing Law)</div>
            <div class="eq-label">Matrix + fluid linear mixing:</div>
            <div class="equation">ρ<sub>b</sub> = (1 − φ) · ρ<sub>m</sub> + φ · ρ<sub>f</sub></div>
            <div class="eq-vars">
                <span>ρ<sub>b</sub></span> bulk density [g/cc]
                <span>φ</span> porosity [v/v]
                <span>ρ<sub>m</sub></span> matrix density [g/cc]
                <span>ρ<sub>f</sub></span> fluid mix density [g/cc]
            </div>
            <div style="margin-top:10px;font-size:10px;color:var(--text-secondary)">
                Fluid fills: SW × ρ<sub>w</sub> + (1−SW) × ρ<sub>hc</sub><br>
                Water ≈ 1.0 · Oil ≈ 0.85 · Gas ≈ 0.001–0.3
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="phys-card">
            <div class="phys-title">NPHI — Neutron Porosity (Hydrogen Index)</div>
            <div class="eq-label">Fluid hydrogen index mixing:</div>
            <div class="equation">NPHI ≈ φ · Σ(S<sub>i</sub> · HI<sub>i</sub>)</div>
            <div class="eq-vars">
                <span>HI<sub>w</sub></span> = 1.0 (bound water)
                <span>HI<sub>oil</sub></span> ≈ 0.95–1.0
                <span>HI<sub>gas</sub></span> ≈ 0.25–0.35
                <span>S<sub>i</sub></span> = saturation fraction
            </div>
            <div style="margin-top:10px;font-size:10px;color:var(--text-secondary)">
                Limestone matrix scale · Negative NPHI = matrix-mineral effect (anhydrite, halite)<br>
                Gas effect: NPHI depressed relative to density porosity
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="phys-card">
            <div class="phys-title">RT — Resistivity (Archie, 1942)</div>
            <div class="eq-label">Clean sand / carbonate:</div>
            <div class="equation">R<sub>t</sub> = a · R<sub>w</sub> / (φ<sup>m</sup> · S<sub>w</sub><sup>n</sup>)</div>
            <div class="eq-vars">
                <span>a</span> = 0.62–1.0 (tortuosity)
                <span>m</span> = 1.5–2.2 (cementation exponent)
                <span>n</span> = 1.8–2.5 (saturation exponent)
                <span>R<sub>w</sub></span> = formation water resistivity
            </div>
            <div style="margin-top:10px;font-size:10px;color:var(--text-secondary)">
                Shaly formations: Simandoux or Indonesia model with explicit C<sub>sh</sub><br>
                Steel/concrete: galvanic casing effect — do not apply Archie
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="phys-card">
            <div class="phys-title">VSH — Shale Volume (GR Linear)</div>
            <div class="eq-label">Gamma ray index method:</div>
            <div class="equation">V<sub>sh</sub> = (GR<sub>log</sub> − GR<sub>min</sub>) / (GR<sub>max</sub> − GR<sub>min</sub>)</div>
            <div class="eq-vars">
                <span>GR<sub>log</sub></span> = measured API
                <span>GR<sub>min</sub></span> = clean sand baseline
                <span>GR<sub>max</sub></span> = shale baseline
            </div>
            <div style="margin-top:10px;font-size:10px;color:var(--text-secondary)">
                Clavier (1971): V<sub>sh</sub> = 1.7 − √(3.4 − I<sub>GR</sub>)<br>
                Larionov older rocks: V<sub>sh</sub> = 0.33(2<sup>IGR</sup> − 1)
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="phys-card" style="margin-bottom:20px">
